    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. that's helpful. u mentioned the \"springing\" thing too - can u explain how that works? also, i'm worried about how to pick someone to be the agent. what should i look for in a person to make sure they'll actually protect his stuff and not just waste it?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A \"springing\" clause is like a magic trigger that only activates the power of attorney once a specific event happens, usually a doctor's official certification that your father has lost the mental capacity to manage his own affairs. Without this clause, the agent might step in immediately just because your dad is confused, which could be a problem if he's just having a bad day or is being stubborn.\n\nWhen choosing an agent, you need someone who is not only reliable but also has a strong moral compass and financial literacy. Think of them as a \"guardian angel\" for your dad's assets, not just a handyman who fixes things but also knows how to keep the house from falling into the ground. Look for someone who is honest, trustworthy, and has a history of being responsible with money. If your dad has a history of gambling or spending recklessly, you might want to avoid someone who has ever been involved in such behavior, as they might not have the discipline to keep the money safe.\n\nAlso, consider having a \"successor agent\" listed in the document. This is like having a backup plan in case your first choice gets sick, moves away, or decides to quit. It ensures that the power of attorney doesn't",
      "source": "target",
